Albert YC Lai (trebla@io.org) writes:

> If I remember correctly, PGP does LZW compression.  Usually PKZip v2
> compresses better than LZW.  (Of course, just my experience.)

PGP uses the compression routines from Info-ZIP. They compress just as
well (and in some cases very slightly better) than PKZIP 2.04g in -ex
mode.

> Uuencode actually expands data.  Hence PGP compresses *way* better than
> uuencode. :)

Maybe the original poster wants to compare the *expansion* between
uuencode and PGP's "ASCII armouring". The should result in one and the
same expansion, although PGP uses longer lines, so the message could
be slightly smaller (because of the fewer EOL characters). In general,
PGP plus ASCII armouring should result in a slightly (but noticeably)
smaller message than PKZIP plus uuencode. Here I am ignoring the
overheads produced by PKZIP and its headers and central directory in
formation, and the encryption headers used by PGP.

Regards,
Vesselin
